library("knitr")
opts_chunk$set(fig.align = "center", fig.width = 10)

Treatment of embroyonic stem cells with retinoic acid stimulates them to differentiate into neural precursors. Thus I expect genes involved in maintenance of the pluripotent state to be affected. To investigate this, I downloaded Table S9 of Dowell et al., 2013 to obtain their list of 354 genes involved in the mouse embryonic stem cell gene regulatory network. They obtained this list from the literature, and used it as a gold standard for finding other genes important for pluripotency.

Calculate log cpm.

normalized_lib_sizes <- calcNormFactors(counts)
log_cpm <- cpm(counts, log = TRUE,
                lib.size = colSums(counts) * normalized_lib_sizes)

Effect of RA treatment on pluripotency genes

Convert to Ensembl gene IDs.

ensembl <- useMart(host = "sep2015.archive.ensembl.org",
                   biomart = "ENSEMBL_MART_ENSEMBL",
                   dataset = "mmusculus_gene_ensembl")
pluri_info <- getBM(attributes = c("ensembl_gene_id", "chromosome_name",
                                  "external_gene_name"),
                      filter = c("external_gene_name", "chromosome_name"),
                      values = list(pluri$name, c(1:19, "MT", "X", "Y")),
                      mart = ensembl)
stopifnot(length(unique(pluri_info$external_gene_name)) == nrow(pluri_info))
head(pluri_info)
##      ensembl_gene_id chromosome_name external_gene_name
## 1 ENSMUSG00000037035               1              Inhbb
## 2 ENSMUSG00000026288               1             Inpp5d
## 3 ENSMUSG00000019699               1               Akt3
## 4 ENSMUSG00000067336               1              Bmpr2
## 5 ENSMUSG00000060743               1              H3f3a
## 6 ENSMUSG00000041075               1               Fzd7

348 of the 354 gene names were successfully converted to Ensembl gene IDs.

Subset the log2 cpm and create an indicator variable for being a pluripotency gene.

log_cpm_pluri <- log_cpm[rownames(log_cpm) %in% pluri_info$ensembl_gene_id, ]
de_results$pluripotent <- rownames(de_results) %in% pluri_info$ensembl_gene_id

299 of the 348 genes with Ensembl annotation are robustly expressed in the current data set.

The heatmap of these pluripotency genes is not very interesting. It separates the treated and untreated just like the full data, and no other clear patterns arise.

heatmap(log_cpm_pluri)

Are pluripotent genes enriched among the differentially expressed genes? I test this using Fishers exact test.

pluri_fisher <- fisher.test(x = de_results$pluripotent, y = de_results$de)
pluri_fisher
## 
##  Fisher's Exact Test for Count Data
## 
## data:  de_results$pluripotent and de_results$de
## p-value = 0.001108
## alternative hypothesis: true odds ratio is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.162193 1.865615
## sample estimates:
## odds ratio 
##   1.472991

Yes, with p-value 0.00. To visualize the enrichment, below are the density plots of the p-values for differential expression for all genes (black line) and the pluripotent genes (red line).

plot(density(de_results$PValue[!de_results$pluripotent]),
     main = "Enrichment of pluripotent genes (red line)",
     xlab = "p-value", xlim = c(0, 1), xaxs = "i")
lines(density(de_results$PValue[de_results$pluripotent]), col = "red")

Visualize Oct4 (Pou5f1), Sox2, and Nanog expression.

pluri_ex <- pluri_info[pluri_info$external_gene_name %in% c("Pou5f1", "Sox2", "Nanog"), ]
log_cpm_pluri_ex <- merge(pluri_ex, log_cpm_pluri, by.x = "ensembl_gene_id",
                          by.y = "row.names")
log_cpm_pluri_ex <- gather(log_cpm_pluri_ex, key = "sample", value = "log_cpm",
                           DMSO.REP1:RA.REP3)
log_cpm_pluri_ex <- separate(log_cpm_pluri_ex, col = sample,
                             into = c("treatment", "replicate"), sep = "\\.")
ggplot(log_cpm_pluri_ex, aes(x = external_gene_name, y = log_cpm, fill = treatment)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(x = "Gene", y = "log2 cpm",
       title = "Expression of key pluripotency genes")

After correcting for multiple testing, only Nanog is significantly differentially expressed. However, they are all downregulated with RA treatment.
